---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Nathan Rasmussen and the custom design, prototyping, 3D printing, painting, finishing, and assembly work behind Nathan Rasmussen Design."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container about-grid">
      <figure class="about-media">
        <img
          src="/images/portfolio/nathan-deer.jpg"
          alt="Nathan with a custom deer display piece."
          width="1200"
          height="800"
        />
      </figure>
      <div class="stack">
        <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
        <h1>I like making ideas real.</h1>
        <p>
          I enjoy taking ideas, whether they begin as a conversation, a sketch, or an existing concept,
          and turning them into finished pieces. Some projects become custom awards, others become display
          pieces, functional designs, or creative one-off builds, but they all share the same goal:
          creating something that feels thoughtfully designed and built to last.
        </p>

        <p>
          My background is in physics and software development, and it naturally influences the way I
          approach fabrication. I enjoy breaking projects into manageable pieces, experimenting with
          different solutions, refining the details, and balancing appearance, function, and practicality.
          That process is just as rewarding to me as the finished object.
        </p>

        <p>
          Over the past several years I've designed, prototyped, 3D printed, painted, and assembled a
          wide variety of projects, from corporate awards and tournament trophies to large display pieces,
          artistic sculptures, and everyday organizational tools. Every project presents a different
          challenge, and that's part of what keeps the work interesting.
        </p>

        <p>
          My favorite project so far has been building a 5½-foot-tall Space Needle. As a Seattle resident,
          it was a project I had wanted to tackle for years. It ultimately required roughly 100 hours of
          design and modeling, 750 hours of printing, and another 100 hours of assembly, sanding, and
          painting. More than anything else I've built, it represents the patience, planning, and
          persistence that I enjoy bringing to ambitious projects.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
